english:
  title: The Words of the White Cloud Recluse
  author: Lee Kyubo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    An old scholar wished to veil his name and sought something to take its place. He reflected thus: "The ancients often chose alternative names and titles. Some took their dwelling places as appellations, others chose what they possessed, and still others embraced their aspirations. Wang Ji became the Master of the Eastern Mound, Du Fu the Sage of the Thatched Hall, He Zhizhang the Mad Guest of Siming, and Bai Juyi the Recluse of Fragrant Mountain—all naming themselves after their dwellings. Tao Qian became the Master of Five Willows, Zheng Xun the Hermit of Seven Pines, and Ouyang Xiu the Recluse of Six Ones—all choosing names from what they possessed. Zhang Zhihe took the title Mysterious Truth, and Yuan Jie the Wandering Elder—both embodying their inner aspirations.

    But I differ from these. I drift like duckweed across the four directions, with no fixed dwelling. I possess no treasured objects, no cultivated aspirations. In all three ways, I fall short of the ancients. What then should my name be?

    Some called me the Sage of the Thatched Hall, but I declined, honoring Du Fu's prior claim. Besides, my thatched dwelling is but a temporary shelter, not a true home. To name myself after each place I lodge would multiply my titles endlessly.

    In life, I have devoted myself to three things: the lute, wine, and poetry. So I first called myself the Master of Three Passions. Yet my playing lacks refinement, my verses are crude, and I scarcely drink deeply—would not the world laugh to see me bear such a name?

    Thus I changed it to the Recluse of White Cloud. Some asked, 'Will you enter the blue mountains and rest upon white clouds? Why such a name?' I answered: 'No. The white cloud is what I admire and seek to emulate. Though I may not achieve its fullness, I can draw near.

    The cloud is a wondrous thing—it rises and disperses, clinging to neither mountain nor sky, drifting freely east and west with form unbound. It transforms in an instant, its scope beyond measure. It expands like a sage emerging into the world and contracts like a sage withdrawing from it. When it brings rain to end the drought, it shows compassion. It arrives without attachment and departs without longing—this is freedom. The colors blue, yellow, red, and black are not the cloud's true nature; only its whiteness, unadorned and unchanging, reveals what it truly is.

    With virtue as deep and color as pure, if one admires and learns from the cloud, one brings blessing to all things when acting in the world and cultivates emptiness of heart when dwelling in stillness. Preserving this whiteness, dwelling in constancy, one enters the realm of Non-Being, uncertain whether the cloud becomes oneself or oneself becomes the cloud. Is this not to approach what the ancients truly attained?'

    Another asked, 'What does it mean to be called a recluse?' I replied, 'Whether dwelling in mountains or in the world, one earns this title only through cherishing the Way. I am one who dwells at home while cherishing the Way.'

    Seeing that my words had touched upon something true, someone said, 'Your insight is clear and should be recorded.' Thus I have written this.
  footnotes:
    - White Cloud (白雲) carries double meaning in Chinese poetic tradition—both literal clouds and the spiritual freedom they represent in Daoist philosophy.
    - The 'realm of Non-Being' (無何有之鄕) references Zhuangzi's concept of ultimate spiritual freedom and detachment.
    - Lee Kyubo adopted this title late in life as a philosophical statement on the contemplative life, distinct from earlier Korean literary figures.
